export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>NERSC reserved 100,800 CPU and 58,800 GPU node-hours for SBIR companies alone in allocation year 2025 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup>; EuroHPC places up to 50,000 GPU-hours with a startup in about four working days <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"442\">[442]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup>. The bottom rungs of the public compute ladder are open to a one-person venture; the top is gated by evidence, not money. This chapter is my operating manual, in the order the doors open.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-1", "html": "<p>Five US and European allocation programs plus one consortium pool cover the path from a laptop to 60% of an exascale machine. Table 19.1 gives the mechanics as of 2026-07-17.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 19.1 — The public compute ladder for a small independent venture (statuses as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Program</th>\n<th>Machine/share</th>\n<th>Award size</th>\n<th>Duration</th>\n<th>Deadline (current cycle)</th>\n<th>Industry/small-company path</th>\n<th>Gate</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>NSF ACCESS</td>\n<td>National Resource-Provider pool (XSEDE successor)</td>\n<td>Small–large</td>\n<td>1 yr</td>\n<td>Rolling/quarterly</td>\n<td>For-profit PIs may apply; SBIR/STTR small businesses &quot;usually eligible&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"441\">[441]</sup></td>\n<td>Open-publication obligation; paid industrial tracks lift it <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"441\">[441]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>EuroHPC AI Factories</td>\n<td>19 sites incl. JUPITER AI Factory, Jülich <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"449\">[449]</sup></td>\n<td>Playground (limited); Fast Lane ≤50,000 GPU-h; Large &gt;50,000 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"442\">[442]</sup></td>\n<td>Per access mode</td>\n<td>Rolling; SME call to 2026-12-31 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup></td>\n<td>Free for AI SMEs/startups; pay-per-use otherwise <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"442\">[442]</sup></td>\n<td>EU/Horizon-associated entity or project; approval ~2 days (Playground), ~4 (Fast Lane) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>ERCAP (NERSC)</td>\n<td>Perlmutter only (80% of NERSC time) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"450\">[450]</sup></td>\n<td>Small–medium; AY2025 SBIR pool: 100,800 CPU + 58,800 GPU node-h <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup></td>\n<td>1 allocation year</td>\n<td>Opens ~Aug, closes early Oct 2026 (AY2027) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup></td>\n<td>Dedicated SBIR pool; all DOE SBIR/STTR projects eligible <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"451\">[451]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup></td>\n<td>Open publishable research only; GPU requests need a code-readiness case <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"451\">[451]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Director's Discretionary (DD)</td>\n<td>~10% of ALCF/OLCF/NERSC <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"450\">[450]</sup></td>\n<td>Small/exploratory</td>\n<td>Rolling</td>\n<td>Anytime</td>\n<td>Open to industry</td>\n<td>Exists to port/tune/scale code for INCITE/ALCC benchmark data <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>ALCC</td>\n<td>Frontier/Aurora/Polaris/Perlmutter (LCFs 30% + NERSC 10%) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"450\">[450]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium–large</td>\n<td>1–3 yr</td>\n<td>2026–27 closed 2026-01-26; next expected ~Nov 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup></td>\n<td>Industrial Partnership User Agreement allows limited proprietary work <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup></td>\n<td>Must already hold external funding (time, not dollars); DOE program-office sponsor <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>INCITE</td>\n<td>Up to 60% of Frontier + Aurora node-hours <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup></td>\n<td>~0.5–1M+ node-h</td>\n<td>Multi-year</td>\n<td>CY2027 closed 2026-06-15; next expected ~Apr 2027 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup></td>\n<td>Explicitly industry-eligible <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup></td>\n<td>Evidence of ≥20%-of-machine readiness; DD benchmarking first <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"447\">[447]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Genesis consortium</td>\n<td>American Science and Security Platform + partner compute/data</td>\n<td>FOA Phase I/II awards (Chapter 17)</td>\n<td>9-mo to 3-yr phases</td>\n<td>Phase I/II closed Apr–May 2026; selections pending <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"418\">[418]</sup></td>\n<td>For-profits on teams spanning ≥2 partner categories <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"418\">[418]</sup></td>\n<td>20% (R&amp;D)/50% (demo) cost share; US-manufacturing clause <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"418\">[418]</sup>; 51-member MOU map <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"420\">[420]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The ladder's asymmetry is the point. Below ERCAP the gates are administrative — eligibility, openness, geography; at ALCC and above they are evidentiary — existing funding, a named sponsor, scaling data. What never appears in the Gate column is money: each rung charges obligations, not fees — publish (ACCESS, ERCAP), collaborate (EuroHPC, Genesis), bring funding (ALCC), bring proof (INCITE). A one-person venture's scarce resource is therefore not cash but credible evidence, which is why §19.3 treats validation artifacts as currency. Two dates anchor planning: ERCAP's AY2027 window and ALCC's expected November 2026 call; INCITE's CY2027 window is closed, making CY2028 my earliest realistic entry.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-1-1", "html": "<p>NSF's ACCESS program is the most explicitly small-business-friendly US instrument: for-profit researchers may apply as PI, and small businesses with strong research capabilities, &quot;such as SBIR or STTR grants,&quot; are usually eligible <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"441\">[441]</sup>. The condition is open publication; paid Resource-Provider industrial tracks lift it <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"441\">[441]</sup>.</p>\n<p>EuroHPC's 19 AI Factories — anchored by the JUPITER AI Factory at Jülich, Europe's first exascale system — are the cheapest credible large compute anywhere: three tiers free to AI small and medium enterprises (SMEs) and startups, Playground access in about two working days, Fast Lane (≤50,000 GPU-hours) approval in about four <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"442\">[442]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"449\">[449]</sup>. The gate is geographic — an EU or Horizon-associated entity or project; the current SME call runs to 2026-12-31 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"442\">[442]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup>. China's parallel on-ramps (Chapter 16) I treat as a later joint-venture option given the domicile and export-control exposure detailed there.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-1-2", "html": "<p>The Energy Research Computing Allocations Process (ERCAP) is the workhorse: small-to-medium allocations at NERSC only, managed by DOE program offices — including a dedicated SBIR pool sized in AY2025 at 100,800 CPU and 58,800 GPU node-hours <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"451\">[451]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup>. Every DOE SBIR/STTR grant project is eligible <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"451\">[451]</sup>. The hard rule shapes strategy: NERSC supports only open, publishable research — purely proprietary work is barred — and GPU requests need a code-readiness justification <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"451\">[451]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup>. For a venture selling validated simulation, that restriction is a feature: the allocation enforces my open-science discipline anyway. The AY2027 window opens around August 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>.</p>\n<p>Director's Discretionary (DD) allocations — roughly 10% of the leadership facilities and NERSC, requestable any time — exist to port, tune, and scale code before INCITE or ALCC <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"450\">[450]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup>. DD is the mandated evidence factory for the top rungs; I run it in parallel from month one — its scaling plots are what those reviewers score.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-1-3", "html": "<p>ALCC is the realistic leadership-class door for a company: medium-to-large awards, now one-to-three-year terms on a single proposal, across Frontier, Aurora, Polaris, and Perlmutter <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup>. Two gates define it — projects must already hold approved external funding (ALCC awards time, never dollars) and must name a DOE program-office sponsor — while its Industrial Partnership User Agreement permits limited proprietary work with public release <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup>. It imposes no INCITE-style scalability requirement <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup>. The 2026–2027 cycle closed 2026-01-26; the next call is expected around November 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>. My rule: ALCC only after federal funding exists — in practice, an SBIR award first.</p>\n<p>INCITE is the flagship: up to 60% of node-hours on Frontier and Aurora, explicitly industry-eligible, typical awards 0.5–1M+ node-hours, multi-year <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup>. The de-facto filter is computational readiness — evidence that production runs can use 20% or more of the full machine effectively <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"447\">[447]</sup>. The CY2027 call closed 2026-06-15; the next is expected around April 2027 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>. My rule is absolute: never apply cold — enter with DD scaling data, ideally inside a lab-led consortium.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-2-1", "html": "<p>The Genesis Mission is both a funding source and a partnering map; the map matters more to me. Its FOA requires small teams spanning at least two partner categories — national laboratories, industry, universities and nonprofits — with for-profits paying 20% cost share on R&amp;D and 50% on demonstration under a &quot;manufactured substantially in the United States&quot; clause <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"418\">[418]</sup>. The 51-member MOU consortium — NVIDIA, AWS, Google, Microsoft, OpenAI, Anthropic among them <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"420\">[420]</sup> — is a published list of the anchors to align with. I enter as a funded sub to a national-lab prime, never as prime; Phase I and II deadlines passed in spring 2026, selections are pending as of 2026-07-17, and Chapter 17 carries the dollar mechanics <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"418\">[418]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"420\">[420]</sup>.</p>\n<p>Lab embedding converts an external applicant into a known quantity. A cooperative research and development agreement (CRADA) pairs a lab's personnel, facilities, and IP with partner funding or in-kind work; the partner keeps its inventions and gets first option to license CRADA-generated lab inventions; small businesses qualify explicitly <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"452\">[452]</sup>. The Lab-Embedded Entrepreneurship Program (LEEP) seats a founder inside Argonne, Oak Ridge, Lawrence Berkeley, or NREL for two years with no equity taken; Chain Reaction Innovations opens Cohort 2027 applications in September 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"430\">[430]</sup>. A CRADA or LEEP seat at a leadership-computing lab is my highest-value partnership target: panels fund people they know, and Argonne's Polybot self-driving laboratory runs as a user tool open to external proposals <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"448\">[448]</sup>.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-3-1", "html": "<p>Three public artifacts form the credibility base layer, built before I request anything above the bottom rungs. First, Matbench Discovery, the de-facto public ranking of universal machine-learning interatomic potentials (MLIPs): its &quot;compliant&quot; track restricts training to the MPtrj dataset to limit data leakage, so a startup competes fairly with Meta and Microsoft <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"97\">[97]</sup>. The top is a recognized credibility event — Meta's models long dominated until EPFL's university-scale PET-OAM-XL took first place in the compliant track in February 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"453\">[453]</sup>.</p>\n<p>Second, OpenKIM: depositing a potential yields a citable KIM ID and a public dashboard of automated Verification Checks — species support, unit conversion, domain decomposition, derivative consistency, invariance — plus LAMMPS/ASE interoperability <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"115\">[115]</sup>. For a venture whose core risk is whether a customer's simulation reproduces its claims, a passing KIM ID is the cheapest trust signal in existence.</p>\n<p>Third, sequenced before everything else: an MS25-style observable-first benchmark on my target alloy class. MS25 (Maxson et al., JCIM 2025) established that low energy and force errors do not guarantee reliable observables — its CH4/Pt case shows a 0.74 eV nudged-elastic-band (NEB) barrier reproduced only within ±0.06 eV even at ~0.2 meV/atom energy error <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>. Mean errors hide barrier-class failure — Chapters 3–12 document the consequences. My first artifact is therefore a public, experiment-anchored benchmark of barriers, phonons, densities, and elastic constants — published before any request beyond ACCESS and EuroHPC. The reason is transactional: DD reviewers want scaling plots, ALCC technical merit, INCITE readiness evidence, industrial partners validated candidates. Validation is the currency; everything above ERCAP is purchased with it.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-3-2", "html": "<p>The societies are where benchmark tasks, data standards, and consortia form; the ladder is present → co-organize → govern, not attend → network → hope. TMS, The Minerals, Metals &amp; Materials Society — the home society for this venture's metals focus, where its industrial and academic leaders convene — draws roughly 4,500 attendees to its annual meeting <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"454\">[454]</sup>. MRS runs an AI Topical Community and an autonomous-materials symposium series <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"455\">[455]</sup>. APS hosts the Topical Group on Data Science, the Division of Materials Physics, and the Forum on Industrial and Applied Physics <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"456\">[456]</sup>. ASM International's Materials Informatics Committee drives industry-wide AI/ML practice <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"457\">[457]</sup>. My order: TMS and ASM first — the metals-and-minerals constituency is my natural partner base — then MRS, then APS. The deliverable is identical everywhere: a validated result with reproducible artifacts, offered as a symposium contribution or data-challenge entry.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-4-1", "html": "<p>Industrial partners buy validated predictions, speed, and IP position — not algorithms, not database volume. Kemira–CuspAI is the ideal made concrete: Kemira defined the brief; CuspAI searched roughly 300 trillion structures, delivered over 5,000 metal-organic framework designs with property data, narrowed them to priority candidates in six months, and continues under a multi-program framework agreement <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup>. Table 19.2 maps the recurring patterns across seven buyer types.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 19.2 — Partnership patterns: who buys, what they buy, through which instrument (as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Partner type</th>\n<th>What they buy</th>\n<th>Documented case</th>\n<th>Instrument</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Specialty-chemicals incumbent</td>\n<td>Validated, narrowed candidate set with property data, on deadline, against their brief</td>\n<td>Kemira–CuspAI: ~300-trillion-structure search → 5,000+ MOF designs → priority candidates in 6 months <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup></td>\n<td>Framework agreement (multi-program)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Battery/materials major</td>\n<td>Co-development plus cathode supply position</td>\n<td>BASF–CATL global cathode framework <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"458\">[458]</sup></td>\n<td>Framework/supply agreement</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Semiconductor equipment + fabs</td>\n<td>Lab-to-fab cycle compression</td>\n<td>Applied Materials EPIC (~$5B; ASU/RPI/Stanford; TSMC/Micron/SK hynix) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"459\">[459]</sup></td>\n<td>Consortium / joint development agreement</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mining major</td>\n<td>Validated exploration predictions plus aligned upside</td>\n<td>KoBold–BHP; majors buying via partnerships and corporate venture <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"460\">[460]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"461\">[461]</sup></td>\n<td>License + consulting + JV earn-in</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Automotive corporate R&amp;D</td>\n<td>Consortium research and open tools</td>\n<td>Toyota Research Institute AMDD (~$10M, 12 universities/labs; spawned startups) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"462\">[462]</sup></td>\n<td>Consortium sponsorship</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Diversified industrial (platform buyer)</td>\n<td>Agentic R&amp;D speed on named problems</td>\n<td>Microsoft Discovery: BHP copper leaching; Syensqo heat-transfer fluids <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"463\">[463]</sup></td>\n<td>Enterprise platform agreement</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Government (anchor customer)</td>\n<td>Domestic supply-chain materials IP</td>\n<td>SandboxAQ–Commerce $500M CHIPS award: PFAS-free chemicals, catalysts, rare-earth-free magnets, batteries <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"429\">[429]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"428\">[428]</sup></td>\n<td>Equity + royalty award</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Three regularities matter at my size. First, the partner owns the brief and the qualification pipeline; the venture's deliverable is a validated, narrowed candidate set with property data on a deadline — speed is the headline, synthesizability and measured data the qualifier <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup>. Second, nobody procures simulation by purchase order: deals arrive as framework agreements, JDAs, consortia, CRADAs, or corporate-venture positions, so the motion is becoming a named node inside an existing structure rather than winning cold contracts. Third, the government row is new and under-priced: equity-plus-royalty turns the state into an anchor customer that shares upside rather than owning the work <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"428\">[428]</sup>. My near-term target is one framework agreement in the Kemira shape — whose validation demands are precisely the artifacts of §19.3.1.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-4-2", "html": "<p>The field is crowded and well-capitalized. The platform layer is free and strong: Microsoft open-sourced MatterGen under MIT <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"464\">[464]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"465\">[465]</sup>; Meta FAIR's OMol25 and UMA models set the open baseline that long topped Matbench Discovery <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"466\">[466]</sup>; NVIDIA's ALCHEMI packages simulation as microservices and selects credible players de facto <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"467\">[467]</sup>. The funded startup tier clusters away from hard materials: CuspAI (<span class=\"math\">$130M closed, MOFs; a further raise above $</span>1B reported but unsigned as of June 2026) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"468\">[468]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"469\">[469]</sup>, Lila Sciences (<span class=\"math\">$550M, broad autonomous laboratories) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"470\">[470]</sup>, Periodic Labs ($</span>300M seed, vertically integrated) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"471\">[471]</sup>, Orbital Industries (<span class=\"math\">$50M Series B, sells hardware rather than software) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"472\">[472]</sup>, Radical AI ($</span>55M seed; alloys for defense, fusion, and semiconductor customers — closest to my territory) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"473\">[473]</sup>, and XtalPi (~$111M 2025 revenue (FY2025; H1 2025 was ¥517m, up 403.8%), first profitable HK-listed AI-for-science firm) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"474\">[474]</sup>. The open gap: validated hard materials — superalloys, ceramics, refractories, magnets, semiconductor process materials — sold as defensible IP with third-party validation; no player has publicly closed a discovery-to-qualified-part loop there.</p>\n<p>Five model patterns demonstrably work; I borrow shapes without writing a business plan. (1) Contract research: XtalPi's discovery-as-a-service reaches profitability because revenue ties to research contracts while downstream risk stays with clients <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"474\">[474]</sup>. (2) Vertical integration: keep the software internal, sell the material or component — Orbital, Radical, Periodic <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"472\">[472]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"473\">[473]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"471\">[471]</sup>. (3) Government equity-plus-royalty R&amp;D: SandboxAQ's $500M CHIPS award funds four domestic materials programs for a minority, non-voting equity stake plus royalties on licensed formulas — a template, politically contested, available now <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"429\">[429]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"428\">[428]</sup>. (4) Open-core seeding: open the base model for credibility — MatterGen, Meta's releases, DPA-2/OpenLAM — while keeping the validated vertical and proprietary data closed <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"464\">[464]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"465\">[465]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"466\">[466]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"475\">[475]</sup>. (5) Autonomous-lab partnership as validation path: partner labs synthesize and characterize my candidates — Polybot as a user tool <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"448\">[448]</sup>, TRI AMDD-style consortia <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"462\">[462]</sup> — and their instruments become my third-party audit. The weak pattern is pure license-the-discovery-to-an-incumbent; Orbital explicitly abandoned it <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"472\">[472]</sup>.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s19-4-3", "html": "<p>Months zero to three: publish the validation artifacts of §19.3.1 — compliant Matbench Discovery submission, OpenKIM deposit with passing Verification Checks, MS25-style observable benchmark on my target alloy class — and apply to NSF ACCESS on the free track and to EuroHPC Playground through an EU collaboration. Nothing here requires permission or money.</p>\n<p>Months three to nine: pursue the federal funding that unlocks the middle rungs (SBIR mechanics in Chapter 17); the moment an award exists, request ERCAP time through the dedicated SBIR pool when the AY2027 call opens around August 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>. In parallel from month one, Director's Discretionary benchmarking — port, tune, scale — generates the readiness plots the top rungs score.</p>\n<p>Months nine to twelve and beyond: ALCC at the next call, expected around November 2026 — only because federal funding will then exist, as its rules require <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>. INCITE never cold: earliest realistic entry is the CY2028 cycle, inside a lab-led consortium, after DD evidence matures. Society track in parallel: a TMS 2027 abstract, MRS's AI Topical Community, ASM's Materials Informatics Committee.</p>\n<p>Every step above is purchased with the same currency: auditable, third-party-checkable validation. That claim wants stress-testing from the other side — what a hostile reviewer, a burned industrial partner, or a journal referee will demand of these artifacts, and whether they survive. Chapter 20 assembles that skeptic register.</p>\n" },
]
